/* CRISC :: content/quiz4.js — CRISC Domain 4 question bank (100 items). */
window.CRISC = window.CRISC || {}; CRISC.questions = CRISC.questions || [];
CRISC.questions.push.apply(CRISC.questions, [
{"id":"D4-001","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"easy","q":"An enterprise architecture (EA) team is planning a multi-year migration to a new ERP platform. From a risk practitioner's perspective, the PRIMARY value of mapping this initiative against the current enterprise architecture is to:","options":["Identify dependencies and inconsistencies that could introduce risk before commitments are made","Reduce the number of vendor demonstrations required","Guarantee the project finishes under budget","Eliminate the need for a post-implementation review"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Identify dependencies and inconsistencies that could introduce risk before commitments are made</strong> — mapping a major technology initiative against the EA surfaces integration gaps, unsupported dependencies, and misalignment with target-state architecture while there is still time to treat the risk cost-effectively.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the number of vendor demonstrations required</b>: EA alignment is a risk and design discipline, not a procurement-scheduling tool.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guarantee the project finishes under budget</b>: no architectural review can guarantee cost outcomes; it only reduces the likelihood of avoidable rework.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for a post-implementation review</b>: a post-implementation review remains necessary regardless of how well the initiative was mapped upfront.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-002","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner notices that several business units have independently approved point-to-point integrations that bypass the enterprise's defined integration layer. What is the GREATEST risk this creates?","options":["Increased architectural complexity and inconsistent control enforcement across undocumented integration paths","Higher licensing costs for the integration platform","Slower user adoption of the new integrations","Reduced need for future capacity planning"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Increased architectural complexity and inconsistent control enforcement across undocumented integration paths</strong> — ad hoc integrations that bypass the governed integration layer create shadow dependencies where security, logging, and change controls may not be consistently applied, raising both operational and security risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Higher licensing costs for the integration platform</b>: bypassing the platform would likely reduce, not increase, licensing costs, so this is not the greatest risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Slower user adoption of the new integrations</b>: adoption speed is a project concern, not the primary architectural risk described.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduced need for future capacity planning</b>: uncontrolled integrations do not reduce capacity planning needs; if anything, they complicate it.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-003","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's target enterprise architecture calls for consolidating on a single cloud provider, but a newly acquired subsidiary runs critical workloads on a competing provider. As the risk practitioner advising on this gap, what should be recommended FIRST?","options":["Perform a risk-based assessment of the migration options and their transition risks before committing to a timeline","Force immediate migration to comply with the target architecture","Ignore the gap since the subsidiary is a separate legal entity","Shut down the subsidiary's workloads until architecture alignment is achieved"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Perform a risk-based assessment of the migration options and their transition risks before committing to a timeline</strong> — before disrupting critical workloads to conform to a target architecture, the practitioner should evaluate the risk of migrating versus the risk of a temporary architectural exception, informing a realistic and safe transition plan.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Force immediate migration to comply with the target architecture</b>: rushing migration of critical workloads without assessing transition risk could cause outages or data loss.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the gap since the subsidiary is a separate legal entity</b>: once acquired, the subsidiary's technology risk becomes part of the enterprise's overall risk profile and cannot be disregarded.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Shut down the subsidiary's workloads until architecture alignment is achieved</b>: this is a disproportionate action that would itself create a severe business disruption risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-004","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"From a risk perspective, the PRIMARY reason an organization enforces a formal change management process for IT operations is to:","options":["Ensure changes are assessed for risk and approved before introducing unintended impacts to production systems","Increase the number of change tickets logged each month","Guarantee that all changes are implemented by external vendors","Eliminate the need for a rollback plan"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Ensure changes are assessed for risk and approved before introducing unintended impacts to production systems</strong> — structured change management exists to evaluate risk, secure appropriate approval, and control the introduction of changes so that unintended disruptions to availability, integrity, or security are minimized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the number of change tickets logged each month</b>: ticket volume is an administrative byproduct, not the purpose of the process.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guarantee that all changes are implemented by external vendors</b>: change management governs the process regardless of who performs the work; it has no bearing on sourcing.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for a rollback plan</b>: a rollback plan remains a necessary safeguard within change management, not something the process removes.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-005","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"A DevOps team has adopted continuous deployment, pushing code to production multiple times per day without a formal change advisory board (CAB) review. As the risk practitioner, what is the MOST appropriate response?","options":["Recommend automated risk-based gates (testing, peer review, rollback automation) embedded in the pipeline in lieu of a manual CAB","Mandate a full manual CAB review before every deployment, regardless of pipeline maturity","Prohibit continuous deployment entirely across the organization","Accept the practice without further evaluation because DevOps teams are self-governing"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Recommend automated risk-based gates (testing, peer review, rollback automation) embedded in the pipeline in lieu of a manual CAB</strong> — high-velocity DevOps environments should replace slow manual gates with automated controls (testing, code review, canary releases, automated rollback) that manage risk without negating the speed benefits of continuous deployment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Mandate a full manual CAB review before every deployment, regardless of pipeline maturity</b>: this reintroduces the bottleneck DevOps is designed to remove and is impractical at the stated deployment frequency.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Prohibit continuous deployment entirely across the organization</b>: an outright ban ignores the legitimate business value of the practice and is disproportionate to the risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the practice without further evaluation because DevOps teams are self-governing</b>: self-governance without embedded controls leaves change risk unmanaged and unmonitored.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-006","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"hard","q":"An IT asset management review reveals that 15% of production servers are not recorded in the configuration management database (CMDB). Which risk should the practitioner escalate as the MOST significant consequence?","options":["The CMDB license may need to be renewed sooner than planned","Unmanaged assets may not receive patches, monitoring, or decommissioning oversight, creating unassessed exposure","Help desk ticket volume may increase slightly","Asset depreciation schedules will be recalculated"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Unmanaged assets may not receive patches, monitoring, or decommissioning oversight, creating unassessed exposure</strong> — assets missing from the CMDB fall outside routine patching, monitoring, and lifecycle processes, meaning vulnerabilities and misconfigurations on those systems may go undetected and untreated.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The CMDB license may need to be renewed sooner than planned</b>: licensing timing is an administrative detail, not a materially significant risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Help desk ticket volume may increase slightly</b>: this is a minor operational side effect, not the central risk of untracked assets.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Asset depreciation schedules will be recalculated</b>: depreciation is a financial accounting matter, unrelated to the security and operational exposure created here.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-007","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"During which phase of the system development life cycle (SDLC) should security and risk requirements FIRST be defined?","options":["Post-implementation review","User acceptance testing","Production support","Requirements/design phase"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Requirements/design phase</strong> — defining security and risk requirements early, during requirements and design, ensures controls are built into the system rather than retrofitted, which is more effective and less costly.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Post-implementation review</b>: this occurs after the system is live and evaluates outcomes; it is far too late to originate requirements.</span> <span class='qd'><b>User acceptance testing</b>: UAT validates that requirements were met, but requirements should already be defined well before this stage.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Production support</b>: this is an ongoing operational phase after go-live, not where requirements are established.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-008","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"A development team is under pressure to release a new customer-facing application by a fixed deadline. Security testing has identified several unresolved medium-risk findings. As the risk practitioner, what is the BEST course of action?","options":["Allow the release to proceed silently since the findings are only medium risk","Present the residual risk to an accountable business owner for a documented go/no-go decision","Delay the release indefinitely until all findings are resolved","Instruct developers to hide the findings from the steering committee to avoid delay"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Present the residual risk to an accountable business owner for a documented go/no-go decision</strong> — the risk practitioner's role is to ensure residual risk is visible to someone with the authority to accept it; a documented, informed decision balances time-to-market pressure against unresolved risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allow the release to proceed silently since the findings are only medium risk</b>: bypassing a formal risk acceptance decision leaves accountability unclear and risk unmanaged.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delay the release indefinitely until all findings are resolved</b>: this ignores the business context and may not be proportionate if the risk is acceptable with compensating controls.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Instruct developers to hide the findings from the steering committee to avoid delay</b>: concealing known risk from decision-makers is unethical and undermines governance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-009","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's SDLC standard requires an independent code security review before production deployment. A project team argues that an automated static analysis scan alone is sufficient and requests a waiver from manual review. What should the risk practitioner evaluate FIRST?","options":["Whether the project team has enough budget remaining for the waiver request","Whether other teams have previously received similar waivers","Whether the application uses open-source components","Whether the automated tool's coverage adequately addresses the risk profile of the application being deployed"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether the automated tool's coverage adequately addresses the risk profile of the application being deployed</strong> — a waiver decision should be risk-based, first determining whether automated scanning provides equivalent assurance for this specific application's risk level (e.g., data sensitivity, exposure) before any control substitution is approved.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the project team has enough budget remaining for the waiver request</b>: budget availability is irrelevant to whether the control substitution is actually adequate to manage risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether other teams have previously received similar waivers</b>: precedent alone does not establish that the substitution is appropriate for this application's specific risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the application uses open-source components</b>: this is a relevant technical detail but not the first, overarching risk question to resolve.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-010","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which stage of the data lifecycle is MOST associated with defining data retention and secure disposal requirements as part of risk treatment?","options":["Data destruction/disposal","Data creation","Data use","Data storage"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Data destruction/disposal</strong> — defining retention periods and secure disposal methods directly governs the end-of-life stage of data, ensuring information is not retained longer than necessary or improperly exposed after use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data creation</b>: this stage addresses classification and initial handling requirements, not disposal.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data use</b>: this stage concerns access and authorized processing, not retention or destruction rules.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data storage</b>: this stage focuses on protecting data at rest, distinct from disposal timing and method.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-011","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"A risk assessment finds that an organization retains customer transaction records indefinitely because no retention policy has been defined. What is the GREATEST risk this creates?","options":["Storage costs will decrease over time","Unnecessary accumulation of sensitive data increases breach impact and potential non-compliance with data minimization requirements","Customer service response times will improve","Backup job durations will shorten"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Unnecessary accumulation of sensitive data increases breach impact and potential non-compliance with data minimization requirements</strong> — retaining data beyond its business need expands the attack surface, increases the impact of any breach, and can violate data minimization principles found in many privacy regulations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storage costs will decrease over time</b>: indefinite retention increases, rather than decreases, storage costs as volume grows.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Customer service response times will improve</b>: retaining excess historical data has no meaningful effect on service response times.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Backup job durations will shorten</b>: larger retained data volumes would lengthen, not shorten, backup windows.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-012","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is migrating archived data to a new platform. Some records are subject to a 7-year regulatory retention requirement, while others have already exceeded their approved retention period. As the risk practitioner, what should be recommended?","options":["Migrate all records to the new platform regardless of retention status","Retain all records permanently to avoid any compliance risk","Migrate only records still within their retention period and securely dispose of records past their approved retention","Delete all archived records to simplify the migration"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Migrate only records still within their retention period and securely dispose of records past their approved retention</strong> — the migration is an ideal control point to enforce the retention schedule, carrying forward only data still required and properly disposing of data that has exceeded its approved lifecycle.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Migrate all records to the new platform regardless of retention status</b>: this perpetuates over-retention risk and disregards the defined schedule.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Retain all records permanently to avoid any compliance risk</b>: over-retention itself creates compliance and breach-impact risk; it is not a safe default.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delete all archived records to simplify the migration</b>: this would improperly destroy records still under a mandatory 7-year retention requirement.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-013","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"easy","q":"In an Agile project, which practice BEST supports early identification and treatment of technology risk throughout delivery?","options":["Deferring all risk assessment until the final release sprint","Incorporating risk review as a recurring item within sprint planning and retrospectives","Assigning risk identification solely to the product owner without team input","Eliminating documentation to accelerate velocity"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Incorporating risk review as a recurring item within sprint planning and retrospectives</strong> — embedding risk discussion into each sprint cycle allows risks to be identified and addressed incrementally, consistent with Agile's iterative delivery model.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Deferring all risk assessment until the final release sprint</b>: waiting until the end contradicts Agile's iterative approach and allows risks to compound unaddressed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assigning risk identification solely to the product owner without team input</b>: risk identification benefits from the full team's technical and functional perspective, not a single role in isolation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminating documentation to accelerate velocity</b>: removing documentation entirely undermines traceability and the ability to manage and communicate risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-014","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"A portfolio of technology projects shows several initiatives consistently exceeding budget and schedule, each approved independently without a consolidated view of resource contention. What is the MOST significant risk this represents?","options":["Individual project managers will require additional certifications","The organization will need to purchase more project management software licenses","Stakeholders will request more frequent status meetings","Poor portfolio-level oversight may allow cumulative resource and delivery risk across projects to go unmanaged"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Poor portfolio-level oversight may allow cumulative resource and delivery risk across projects to go unmanaged</strong> — without portfolio-level visibility, competing projects can strain shared resources and compound schedule/budget risk in ways that project-by-project approval fails to detect or mitigate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Individual project managers will require additional certifications</b>: certification needs are a staffing development matter, not the core portfolio risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will need to purchase more project management software licenses</b>: tooling needs are a minor operational detail, not the significant risk exposed here.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Stakeholders will request more frequent status meetings</b>: meeting cadence is a communication preference, not a materialized risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-015","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is reviewing a project portfolio and finds that a high-value initiative with significant strategic risk exposure has the same governance oversight level as a low-value administrative project. What should be recommended?","options":["Apply identical governance to all projects to ensure fairness","Remove governance from low-value projects entirely","Apply risk-tiered governance so oversight intensity is proportionate to each project's risk and value","Increase governance only for projects requested by external auditors"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Apply risk-tiered governance so oversight intensity is proportionate to each project's risk and value</strong> — portfolio governance should scale oversight, reporting frequency, and approval authority to the risk and strategic value of each project, ensuring high-exposure initiatives receive commensurate scrutiny.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Apply identical governance to all projects to ensure fairness</b>: uniform governance regardless of risk wastes oversight capacity on low-risk work while potentially under-scrutinizing high-risk work.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove governance from low-value projects entirely</b>: even low-value projects need baseline oversight to prevent risk from being unmanaged.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase governance only for projects requested by external auditors</b>: governance intensity should be risk-driven, not reactive to audit requests alone.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-016","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"The recovery time objective (RTO) for a critical application is PRIMARILY used to determine:","options":["The amount of data that can be lost during an outage","The number of end users affected by an outage","The maximum acceptable duration for restoring the application after a disruption","The annual budget allocated to the application"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The maximum acceptable duration for restoring the application after a disruption</strong> — RTO defines how quickly a system must be recovered to avoid unacceptable business impact, directly shaping resilience strategy and investment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The amount of data that can be lost during an outage</b>: this describes the recovery point objective (RPO), a distinct metric from RTO.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of end users affected by an outage</b>: user count may inform impact analysis but is not what RTO itself measures.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The annual budget allocated to the application</b>: budget is a resourcing decision, not a resilience metric.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-017","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"A business impact analysis reveals that a critical payment system's actual recovery capability is 12 hours, but the business requires an RTO of 4 hours. As the risk practitioner, what should be recommended?","options":["Update the BIA to reflect a 12-hour RTO so the gap disappears on paper","Treat the resilience gap by investing in faster recovery capability or formally accepting the residual risk at an appropriate authority level","Ignore the gap since the system has not failed recently","Transfer all responsibility for recovery to the cloud hosting provider without further action"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Treat the resilience gap by investing in faster recovery capability or formally accepting the residual risk at an appropriate authority level</strong> — when actual recovery capability falls short of the business-defined RTO, the gap must be closed through investment (e.g., redundancy, faster failover) or knowingly accepted by someone with the authority to do so.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Update the BIA to reflect a 12-hour RTO so the gap disappears on paper</b>: silently changing the requirement to match current capability hides real business risk rather than managing it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the gap since the system has not failed recently</b>: absence of a recent failure does not eliminate the exposure; the gap remains until a disruption occurs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Transfer all responsibility for recovery to the cloud hosting provider without further action</b>: provider SLAs rarely fully absorb business-level recovery accountability, and this abdicates necessary oversight.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-018","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's disaster recovery test for a critical data center revealed that failover to the secondary site took 9 hours against a defined RTO of 6 hours, primarily due to manual, undocumented recovery steps performed by a single engineer. What is the MOST important risk to address FIRST?","options":["Key person dependency and lack of documented, repeatable recovery procedures","The color scheme of the recovery site's signage","The number of vendors used for the primary data center","The frequency of scheduled fire drills"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Key person dependency and lack of documented, repeatable recovery procedures</strong> — reliance on one individual's undocumented knowledge is a single point of failure that directly caused the RTO breach; documenting and automating the recovery process addresses the root cause of the resilience gap.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The color scheme of the recovery site's signage</b>: this is a trivial facility detail with no bearing on recovery time.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of vendors used for the primary data center</b>: vendor count at the primary site is unrelated to the documented failure cause at the secondary site.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The frequency of scheduled fire drills</b>: fire drills address life-safety evacuation, not IT system recovery procedures.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-019","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"easy","q":"When an organization is evaluating adoption of a public cloud infrastructure-as-a-service (IaaS) offering, which of the following is a PRIMARY risk consideration unique to the shared responsibility model?","options":["Selecting the provider with the lowest advertised monthly cost","Clearly delineating which security controls the provider manages versus which remain the customer's responsibility","Choosing a provider based solely on brand recognition","Avoiding any contractual review of the service agreement"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Clearly delineating which security controls the provider manages versus which remain the customer's responsibility</strong> — in IaaS, misunderstanding the shared responsibility boundary is a leading cause of unaddressed security gaps, since customers remain accountable for controls the provider does not manage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Selecting the provider with the lowest advertised monthly cost</b>: cost alone does not address the risk of misunderstood control ownership.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Choosing a provider based solely on brand recognition</b>: brand reputation does not substitute for a clear understanding of control responsibilities.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoiding any contractual review of the service agreement</b>: skipping contract review would increase, not decrease, risk exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-020","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"An organization is piloting an AI-based fraud detection model in production. As the risk practitioner, which risk is MOST important to evaluate before full deployment?","options":["The potential for model bias, drift, and false positives/negatives to produce unreliable or inequitable decisions","Whether the vendor's marketing materials use industry-standard terminology","Whether the model's user interface uses the corporate color palette","The number of competitors already using similar AI tools"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The potential for model bias, drift, and false positives/negatives to produce unreliable or inequitable decisions</strong> — AI/ML models introduce risks around accuracy degradation over time, embedded bias, and erroneous outcomes that can cause financial, reputational, or regulatory harm if not validated and monitored.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the vendor's marketing materials use industry-standard terminology</b>: marketing language has no bearing on the model's actual risk profile.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the model's user interface uses the corporate color palette</b>: visual branding is a cosmetic concern, not a risk consideration.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of competitors already using similar AI tools</b>: competitor adoption does not inform this organization's specific risk exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-021","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"hard","q":"An organization deploys a large fleet of IoT sensors across its manufacturing plants to support predictive maintenance. Many devices ship with default credentials and cannot be patched remotely. As the risk practitioner, what is the MOST effective treatment to recommend?","options":["Connect all IoT devices directly to the corporate network for simplicity","Accept the risk without any compensating controls since production cannot be interrupted","Disable network monitoring on the IoT segment to reduce alert volume","Segment IoT devices onto an isolated network with strict access controls and compensating monitoring, since the devices themselves cannot be hardened directly"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Segment IoT devices onto an isolated network with strict access controls and compensating monitoring, since the devices themselves cannot be hardened directly</strong> — when devices cannot be patched or reconfigured, network segmentation and monitoring serve as compensating controls that limit the blast radius and enable detection of anomalous activity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Connect all IoT devices directly to the corporate network for simplicity</b>: this would expose the broader network to vulnerable, unpatchable devices, significantly increasing risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the risk without any compensating controls since production cannot be interrupted</b>: accepting risk without exploring reasonable compensating controls is premature and unnecessarily exposes the enterprise.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disable network monitoring on the IoT segment to reduce alert volume</b>: removing monitoring eliminates the ability to detect compromise, worsening rather than treating the risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-022","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the PRIMARY purpose of adopting a recognized security control framework such as ISO/IEC 27001 or NIST CSF?","options":["To guarantee complete immunity from security incidents","To provide a structured, repeatable baseline for selecting and managing controls proportionate to risk","To eliminate the need for a risk assessment","To satisfy a single specific regulatory audit and nothing further"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>To provide a structured, repeatable baseline for selecting and managing controls proportionate to risk</strong> — recognized frameworks give organizations a consistent, defensible structure for identifying, implementing, and maintaining controls aligned to their risk profile.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To guarantee complete immunity from security incidents</b>: no framework can eliminate incident risk entirely; frameworks manage, not eliminate, risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for a risk assessment</b>: risk assessment is a foundational, ongoing component within these frameworks, not something they replace.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To satisfy a single specific regulatory audit and nothing further</b>: frameworks serve an ongoing risk management purpose well beyond any one compliance exercise.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-023","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"An organization has adopted a security framework but implements only the controls explicitly required by its primary regulator, ignoring other framework guidance. What risk should the practitioner MOST highlight?","options":["A compliance-only approach may leave material risks unaddressed that the regulation does not specifically cover","The organization will face immediate regulatory fines for over-compliance","Framework adoption costs will increase indefinitely","Employees will require less security awareness training"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A compliance-only approach may leave material risks unaddressed that the regulation does not specifically cover</strong> — regulations typically represent a minimum baseline; treating the framework as a checklist limited to regulatory scope can leave genuine risks to the business unaddressed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will face immediate regulatory fines for over-compliance</b>: there is no such thing as being penalized for exceeding minimum requirements; this option misstates the risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Framework adoption costs will increase indefinitely</b>: selectively applying only regulatory-required controls would likely reduce, not increase, near-term costs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Employees will require less security awareness training</b>: training needs are unrelated to which controls are selected from the framework.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-024","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is comparing two candidate control frameworks for a global organization: one is prescriptive and highly detailed, the other is principles-based and flexible. Operations span multiple regulatory jurisdictions with differing requirements. Which factor should MOST influence the selection?","options":["Which framework has the shorter published document","Which framework is used by the organization's largest competitor","The framework's ability to be tailored to diverse regulatory and operational contexts while remaining auditable","Which framework requires the least executive involvement"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The framework's ability to be tailored to diverse regulatory and operational contexts while remaining auditable</strong> — a global, multi-jurisdictional organization needs a framework flexible enough to adapt to varying legal requirements while still providing consistent, demonstrable control assurance across the enterprise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which framework has the shorter published document</b>: document length is irrelevant to whether the framework fits the organization's complex regulatory footprint.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which framework is used by the organization's largest competitor</b>: competitor choice does not reflect this organization's own regulatory and operational needs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Which framework requires the least executive involvement</b>: minimizing executive involvement is counter to effective governance and control ownership.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-025","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"Applying the principle of least privilege to a new employee's system access is PRIMARILY intended to:","options":["Grant broad access up front to minimize future access requests","Ensure every employee has identical access regardless of role","Eliminate the need for periodic access reviews","Limit access rights to only what is necessary to perform assigned job duties, reducing potential exposure"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Limit access rights to only what is necessary to perform assigned job duties, reducing potential exposure</strong> — least privilege minimizes the attack surface and potential impact of compromised credentials or insider misuse by restricting access to the minimum needed for the role.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Grant broad access up front to minimize future access requests</b>: this directly contradicts least privilege and increases risk exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ensure every employee has identical access regardless of role</b>: access should be role-based and tailored, not uniform across all positions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for periodic access reviews</b>: least privilege at provisioning does not remove the ongoing need to review and recertify access over time.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-026","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"An access review reveals that a former project team's shared service account, used to grant temporary elevated access, was never disabled after the project ended eight months ago. What is the GREATEST risk this represents?","options":["The organization will incur additional licensing fees for the unused account","An unmonitored, still-active privileged account could be exploited without attribution to a specific individual","Help desk staff will need to reset the password more frequently","The project's documentation will need to be archived sooner"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>An unmonitored, still-active privileged account could be exploited without attribution to a specific individual</strong> — a lingering shared privileged account that should have been decommissioned represents unmanaged access that, if compromised or misused, cannot be traced to an individual, undermining accountability and increasing breach impact.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will incur additional licensing fees for the unused account</b>: licensing cost is a minor administrative concern, not the primary security risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Help desk staff will need to reset the password more frequently</b>: password reset frequency is unrelated to the core risk of an orphaned privileged account.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The project's documentation will need to be archived sooner</b>: documentation timing has no bearing on the access risk described.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-027","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is selecting a control to treat the risk of credential compromise for administrators who manage the organization's core financial systems. Which control BEST reduces this specific risk?","options":["A quarterly newsletter reminding administrators to use strong passwords","Increasing the frequency of full system backups","Multi-factor authentication combined with privileged access management (PAM) and session monitoring","Requiring administrators to memorize a longer password without other controls"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Multi-factor authentication combined with privileged access management (PAM) and session monitoring</strong> — layering MFA with PAM controls and session monitoring directly reduces the likelihood and impact of compromised privileged credentials by adding authentication assurance, controlled checkout, and detective oversight.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A quarterly newsletter reminding administrators to use strong passwords</b>: awareness communication alone is a weak, non-technical control insufficient to address privileged credential risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increasing the frequency of full system backups</b>: backups support recovery after an incident but do not prevent or reduce the likelihood of credential compromise.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Requiring administrators to memorize a longer password without other controls</b>: a longer password alone, without MFA or monitoring, is a single, insufficient layer of defense for high-value accounts.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-028","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"An organization implements role-based access control (RBAC) but has not reviewed role definitions in three years, resulting in significant role overlap and excessive entitlements. As the risk practitioner, what should be recommended FIRST?","options":["Immediately revoke all user access until roles are redefined","Replace RBAC with unrestricted access for simplicity","Conduct a role and entitlement review to realign access with current job functions and eliminate unnecessary overlap","Delegate the entire access model redesign to end users"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Conduct a role and entitlement review to realign access with current job functions and eliminate unnecessary overlap</strong> — a structured review identifies where role definitions have drifted from actual job needs, enabling the organization to right-size entitlements and restore the effectiveness of RBAC.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately revoke all user access until roles are redefined</b>: this would halt business operations and is a disproportionate first step.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replace RBAC with unrestricted access for simplicity</b>: removing access controls entirely would dramatically increase risk rather than address the overlap problem.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delegate the entire access model redesign to end users</b>: end users lack the enterprise visibility needed to redesign access governance appropriately.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-029","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"Segregation of duties (SoD) is PRIMARILY intended to reduce the risk of:","options":["Slower system performance due to excessive access requests","Increased help desk call volume","A single individual having sufficient access to both perform and conceal a fraudulent or erroneous action","Reduced employee morale from restricted access"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A single individual having sufficient access to both perform and conceal a fraudulent or erroneous action</strong> — SoD divides critical tasks among multiple people so that no one person can both execute and cover up an improper action without collusion.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Slower system performance due to excessive access requests</b>: system performance is a technical/capacity issue unrelated to the purpose of SoD.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increased help desk call volume</b>: this is an operational side effect, not the risk SoD is designed to address.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduced employee morale from restricted access</b>: morale is a secondary human-factors consideration, not the control's primary risk objective.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-030","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"A small finance team cannot fully implement segregation of duties between invoice creation and payment approval due to limited headcount. Which compensating control would MOST effectively treat this risk?","options":["Granting all finance staff full administrative rights to simplify workflows","Removing all approval requirements to speed up payment processing","Independent management review and reconciliation of invoice and payment logs on a regular basis","Outsourcing the entire finance function without oversight"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Independent management review and reconciliation of invoice and payment logs on a regular basis</strong> — when true SoD cannot be achieved due to staffing constraints, a detective compensating control such as periodic independent review helps identify irregularities that preventive separation would otherwise catch.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting all finance staff full administrative rights to simplify workflows</b>: this worsens the underlying SoD risk rather than compensating for it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing all approval requirements to speed up payment processing</b>: eliminating approval entirely removes a key control rather than compensating for limited staffing.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Outsourcing the entire finance function without oversight</b>: outsourcing without oversight does not address the control gap and introduces new third-party risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-031","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"The PRIMARY purpose of ongoing security and risk awareness training for all staff is to:","options":["Reduce the likelihood of human error and social engineering success by reinforcing secure behaviors","Satisfy a one-time onboarding requirement with no further reinforcement needed","Replace the need for technical security controls","Reduce the size of the security budget"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Reduce the likelihood of human error and social engineering success by reinforcing secure behaviors</strong> — since employees are frequently the target of phishing and social engineering, ongoing training reinforces vigilance and reduces the human-factor risk that technical controls alone cannot fully mitigate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Satisfy a one-time onboarding requirement with no further reinforcement needed</b>: effective awareness training must be ongoing, as threats and behaviors evolve over time.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for technical security controls</b>: awareness training complements, but does not substitute for, technical and procedural controls.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the size of the security budget</b>: training is an investment intended to reduce risk, not a budget-reduction mechanism.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-032","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"Phishing simulation results show that the same group of employees repeatedly clicks on simulated malicious links despite completing annual training. What should the risk practitioner recommend?","options":["Terminate the employees who clicked the simulated link","Discontinue phishing simulations since they are ineffective","Provide no further training since annual training was already completed","Targeted, role-specific remedial training and reinforcement for the repeat-offender group, rather than only generic annual training"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Targeted, role-specific remedial training and reinforcement for the repeat-offender group, rather than only generic annual training</strong> — repeated susceptibility indicates that generic annual training is insufficient for this group; focused, more frequent reinforcement tailored to their specific gaps is a more effective risk treatment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Terminate the employees who clicked the simulated link</b>: this is a disproportionate punitive response to a training and awareness gap, not a measured risk treatment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Discontinue phishing simulations since they are ineffective</b>: the simulations are working as intended by identifying a real gap; discontinuing them removes valuable risk visibility.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Provide no further training since annual training was already completed</b>: the repeated failures show the existing training cadence and content are inadequate for this group.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-033","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"hard","q":"An organization's security culture survey reveals that employees understand policy requirements but frequently bypass controls because doing so is faster and rarely challenged by management. As the risk practitioner, what is the ROOT issue to address?","options":["Insufficient technical detail in the training content","A lack of consistent management reinforcement and accountability for secure behavior, beyond knowledge alone","The need for a longer annual training course","A lack of translated training materials"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A lack of consistent management reinforcement and accountability for secure behavior, beyond knowledge alone</strong> — the survey shows a knowledge-behavior gap driven by culture: employees know the rules but are not held accountable, indicating the fix lies in management reinforcement and accountability, not additional content.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Insufficient technical detail in the training content</b>: the scenario states employees already understand the requirements, so additional technical detail would not resolve the behavioral gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The need for a longer annual training course</b>: length of training is not the issue; the problem is unenforced accountability, not lack of coverage.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A lack of translated training materials</b>: nothing in the scenario suggests a language barrier is the cause.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-034","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"easy","q":"Which control is PRIMARILY intended to protect the confidentiality of sensitive data while it is stored on a laptop hard drive?","options":["Full-disk encryption","Network intrusion detection","Antivirus signature updates","Change management approval workflow"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Full-disk encryption</strong> — encrypting the entire disk protects data at rest so that, if the device is lost or stolen, the information remains unreadable without the decryption key.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Network intrusion detection</b>: this detects malicious network activity, not protection of data stored locally on a device.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Antivirus signature updates</b>: this addresses malware detection, not confidentiality protection of data at rest.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Change management approval workflow</b>: this governs authorized changes to systems, unrelated to data-at-rest confidentiality.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-035","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"A risk assessment finds that customer personal data is being copied to unmanaged personal devices by employees working remotely, outside the organization's data loss prevention (DLP) coverage. What is the MOST effective treatment?","options":["Prohibit all remote work company-wide","Ignore the finding since remote work improves productivity","Extend DLP and access controls to cover remote work scenarios, or restrict sensitive data access to managed devices only","Increase the marketing budget to offset potential reputational damage"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Extend DLP and access controls to cover remote work scenarios, or restrict sensitive data access to managed devices only</strong> — closing the visibility and control gap by extending DLP coverage or limiting sensitive data access to managed, compliant devices directly treats the identified exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Prohibit all remote work company-wide</b>: this is a disproportionate response to a control gap that can be addressed with more targeted technical measures.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the finding since remote work improves productivity</b>: dismissing a genuine confidentiality risk because of an unrelated business benefit fails basic risk management practice.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the marketing budget to offset potential reputational damage</b>: this addresses a hypothetical downstream consequence rather than treating the actual data protection gap.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-036","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating whether to adopt pseudonymization or full anonymization for a dataset used in an analytics project that may later need to be linked back to specific customers for support purposes. Which approach BEST balances the competing needs of privacy risk reduction and business utility?","options":["Full anonymization, since it always provides stronger business utility","Pseudonymization, since it reduces direct identifiability while preserving the ability to re-link data when properly authorized","Neither technique, since raw identifiable data provides the most flexibility","Full anonymization, since re-linking is never a legitimate business requirement"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Pseudonymization, since it reduces direct identifiability while preserving the ability to re-link data when properly authorized</strong> — pseudonymization replaces direct identifiers with tokens while retaining a controlled mechanism to re-identify data when there is a legitimate, authorized business need, unlike anonymization which is designed to be irreversible.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full anonymization, since it always provides stronger business utility</b>: true anonymization is generally irreversible, which would prevent the stated need to re-link data for support purposes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither technique, since raw identifiable data provides the most flexibility</b>: using raw identifiable data unnecessarily maximizes privacy risk and disregards data minimization principles.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full anonymization, since re-linking is never a legitimate business requirement</b>: the scenario explicitly states a legitimate future need to re-link data, which anonymization would prevent.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-037","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"An enterprise architecture roadmap identifies a plan to retire a legacy mainframe application over the next three years, but no interim risk treatment has been defined for known vulnerabilities on that system during the transition period. What should the risk practitioner recommend?","options":["Implement compensating controls to manage the legacy system's risk until decommissioning is complete","Immediately decommission the system without a transition plan","Postpone the entire architecture roadmap until the mainframe issue is irrelevant","Accept the risk permanently since decommissioning is already planned"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Implement compensating controls to manage the legacy system's risk until decommissioning is complete</strong> — a multi-year transition period leaves known vulnerabilities exposed in the interim, so compensating controls (segmentation, enhanced monitoring, restricted access) are needed to manage risk until the planned retirement is realized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately decommission the system without a transition plan</b>: abrupt decommissioning without a transition plan risks disrupting dependent business processes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Postpone the entire architecture roadmap until the mainframe issue is irrelevant</b>: delaying the broader roadmap is disproportionate and unnecessary if interim controls can manage the risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the risk permanently since decommissioning is already planned</b>: a planned future retirement does not eliminate the need to manage known risk during the interim period.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-038","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"An emergency change is made to a production system outside the normal change management process to resolve an active outage. What is the MOST important follow-up action from a risk perspective?","options":["Retrospectively document, review, and formally approve the emergency change to ensure it meets control and audit requirements","Avoid documenting the change to prevent drawing attention to the outage","Reverse the emergency change immediately regardless of outcome","Wait until the next annual audit to address the emergency change"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Retrospectively document, review, and formally approve the emergency change to ensure it meets control and audit requirements</strong> — emergency changes bypass normal controls out of necessity, so a timely retrospective review and approval closes the control gap, validates the change was appropriate, and maintains an auditable record.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Avoid documenting the change to prevent drawing attention to the outage</b>: failing to document an emergency change undermines governance, accountability, and audit trail integrity.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reverse the emergency change immediately regardless of outcome</b>: reversing a change that successfully resolved an outage, without cause, could reintroduce the original disruption.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Wait until the next annual audit to address the emergency change</b>: delaying review for a year leaves an unauthorized or unreviewed change unaddressed for far too long.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-039","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"Incorporating a risk assessment early in the SDLC's design phase PRIMARILY helps the organization to:","options":["Skip user acceptance testing entirely","Eliminate the need for future patch management","Guarantee zero defects in the final product","Address security and control requirements at lower cost than remediating them after deployment"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Address security and control requirements at lower cost than remediating them after deployment</strong> — identifying risks during design allows controls to be architected in from the start, which is significantly cheaper and more effective than retrofitting fixes after the system is built or live.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Skip user acceptance testing entirely</b>: early risk assessment does not replace the need for UAT to validate functional and control requirements.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for future patch management</b>: ongoing patching remains necessary throughout the system's life regardless of early design-phase risk work.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guarantee zero defects in the final product</b>: no amount of early risk assessment can guarantee a completely defect-free product.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-040","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"A data classification policy requires that highly confidential data be encrypted both at rest and in transit. An assessment finds that a third-party file-sharing tool used by staff transmits data in plaintext. What is the MOST appropriate risk treatment?","options":["Accept the risk since the tool improves collaboration efficiency","Reclassify the data as public to eliminate the encryption requirement","Disable the organization's data classification policy","Replace or reconfigure the tool to enforce encryption in transit, or restrict its use for highly confidential data"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Replace or reconfigure the tool to enforce encryption in transit, or restrict its use for highly confidential data</strong> — the identified gap directly violates the data protection requirement for highly confidential data, so the tool must be brought into compliance or its use restricted for that data class.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the risk since the tool improves collaboration efficiency</b>: accepting a clear policy violation for convenience disregards the defined protection requirement without justification.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reclassify the data as public to eliminate the encryption requirement</b>: reclassifying data to avoid a control requirement misrepresents its actual sensitivity and is not a legitimate treatment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disable the organization's data classification policy</b>: removing the policy eliminates governance rather than addressing the specific gap identified.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-041","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"A project using an Agile delivery model plans to integrate with a legacy system that has known, unpatched vulnerabilities. The project backlog does not currently include any risk treatment items for this integration. What should the risk practitioner recommend?","options":["Remove all references to the legacy system from project documentation","Proceed with integration and address risk only if an incident occurs","Add risk treatment as prioritized backlog items so the team addresses the integration risk within the sprint cycle","Cancel the Agile project and revert to a waterfall methodology"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Add risk treatment as prioritized backlog items so the team addresses the integration risk within the sprint cycle</strong> — embedding risk treatment directly into the backlog ensures the known vulnerability is addressed through the team's normal iterative workflow rather than being overlooked.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove all references to the legacy system from project documentation</b>: hiding the risk from documentation does not treat it and undermines transparency.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Proceed with integration and address risk only if an incident occurs</b>: this is a reactive approach that leaves a known vulnerability unaddressed until after harm occurs.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cancel the Agile project and revert to a waterfall methodology</b>: changing methodology does not address the specific integration risk and is a disproportionate response.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-042","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY reason organizations conduct periodic disaster recovery (DR) testing rather than relying on documentation alone?","options":["To satisfy a requirement to use the recovery site facility at least once a year","To reduce the total cost of the DR program","To validate that recovery procedures and RTO/RPO targets can actually be achieved in practice","To eliminate the need for a business impact analysis"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To validate that recovery procedures and RTO/RPO targets can actually be achieved in practice</strong> — testing confirms whether documented plans genuinely work under realistic conditions, revealing gaps that paper reviews alone cannot uncover.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>To satisfy a requirement to use the recovery site facility at least once a year</b>: facility usage frequency is not the purpose of testing; validating recovery capability is.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To reduce the total cost of the DR program</b>: testing typically adds cost in the near term rather than reducing it; its value is risk assurance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>To eliminate the need for a business impact analysis</b>: the BIA remains a foundational input to DR planning and is not replaced by testing.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-043","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"An organization is evaluating a software-as-a-service (SaaS) provider for a core HR system. The provider will host all employee personal data. Which risk consideration should the practitioner prioritize FIRST?","options":["The visual design of the provider's user interface","The provider's stock price performance over the past year","The number of unrelated products the provider also sells","The provider's data protection, security certifications, and contractual accountability for a breach"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>The provider's data protection, security certifications, and contractual accountability for a breach</strong> — since the provider will hold sensitive employee data, the organization must prioritize assurance over the provider's security posture and clear contractual accountability before onboarding.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The visual design of the provider's user interface</b>: interface aesthetics have no bearing on data protection risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The provider's stock price performance over the past year</b>: stock performance is a financial indicator, not a direct measure of security or data protection capability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The number of unrelated products the provider also sells</b>: product breadth is irrelevant to the specific risk of hosting sensitive HR data.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-044","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Mapping an organization's internal controls to a recognized framework such as COBIT is MOST useful for:","options":["Automatically remediating all identified vulnerabilities","Replacing the need for management review of controls","Identifying control gaps and providing a common reference structure for assessing control maturity","Eliminating the requirement for external audits"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Identifying control gaps and providing a common reference structure for assessing control maturity</strong> — mapping to a recognized framework gives a consistent lens for identifying missing or weak controls and benchmarking maturity, supporting more informed risk decisions.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Automatically remediating all identified vulnerabilities</b>: mapping is an assessment activity; it does not itself fix or remediate anything.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replacing the need for management review of controls</b>: management review remains essential regardless of framework mapping.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminating the requirement for external audits</b>: framework mapping does not remove external audit obligations that may still apply.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-045","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"An organization is implementing single sign-on (SSO) across its application portfolio. From a risk perspective, which of the following is the MOST important control to pair with SSO?","options":["Removing all password complexity requirements to simplify the user experience","Allowing unlimited login attempts to reduce help desk calls","Strong multi-factor authentication at the SSO identity provider, since a compromised SSO credential now grants access to many systems","Disabling logging on the identity provider to improve performance"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Strong multi-factor authentication at the SSO identity provider, since a compromised SSO credential now grants access to many systems</strong> — SSO concentrates authentication risk at a single point, so strengthening that point with MFA is essential to prevent one compromised credential from cascading across the entire application portfolio.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Removing all password complexity requirements to simplify the user experience</b>: weakening password requirements would increase, not decrease, the risk that SSO consolidation introduces.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing unlimited login attempts to reduce help desk calls</b>: this would make brute-force attacks easier against the single point of authentication, increasing risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disabling logging on the identity provider to improve performance</b>: removing logging eliminates critical visibility needed to detect misuse of the consolidated identity system.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-046","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"Embedding security awareness metrics (e.g., phishing click rates, training completion) into risk reporting to executives PRIMARILY helps to:","options":["Replace the need for technical vulnerability metrics entirely","Guarantee that no employee will ever fall for a phishing attempt","Demonstrate the human-factor dimension of risk exposure and track improvement over time","Reduce the frequency of required security awareness training"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Demonstrate the human-factor dimension of risk exposure and track improvement over time</strong> — awareness metrics give executives visibility into the human element of risk, complementing technical metrics and showing whether training investments are reducing susceptibility over time.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Replace the need for technical vulnerability metrics entirely</b>: awareness metrics complement, rather than replace, technical risk indicators.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guarantee that no employee will ever fall for a phishing attempt</b>: no training metric can guarantee elimination of human error.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the frequency of required security awareness training</b>: reporting metrics does not itself justify reducing training cadence; results should drive that decision.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-047","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"An organization plans to use a third-party analytics vendor that requires access to raw, identifiable customer data for a marketing project. A risk practitioner determines the project's objectives could be achieved using aggregated, de-identified data instead. What principle supports recommending the de-identified approach?","options":["Data replication, ensuring multiple redundant copies of the same dataset","Data minimization, limiting exposure of personal data to what is strictly necessary for the stated purpose","Data classification, assigning a sensitivity label after the fact","Data virtualization, abstracting the physical storage location"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Data minimization, limiting exposure of personal data to what is strictly necessary for the stated purpose</strong> — using de-identified, aggregated data instead of raw identifiable records directly applies the data minimization principle, reducing privacy risk while still meeting the business objective.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data replication, ensuring multiple redundant copies of the same dataset</b>: replication concerns redundancy and availability, not limiting the scope of personal data shared.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data classification, assigning a sensitivity label after the fact</b>: classification labels data but does not itself reduce the volume or identifiability of data shared with the vendor.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Data virtualization, abstracting the physical storage location</b>: virtualization is a storage architecture concept unrelated to reducing personal data exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-048","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"A technology roadmap review reveals that two business units have each independently procured competing customer relationship management (CRM) platforms. As the risk practitioner, what is the GREATEST concern to raise?","options":["The organization will need to negotiate two separate support contracts","Employees will need training on two different interfaces","Fragmented architecture increases integration risk, duplicate data stores, and inconsistent control application across customer data","Marketing reports will take slightly longer to compile"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Fragmented architecture increases integration risk, duplicate data stores, and inconsistent control application across customer data</strong> — duplicate, uncoordinated platforms holding customer data increase the risk of inconsistent security controls, data quality issues, and integration complexity across the enterprise.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will need to negotiate two separate support contracts</b>: contract administration is a procurement inconvenience, not the greatest underlying risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Employees will need training on two different interfaces</b>: training overhead is a manageable operational cost, secondary to the architectural and data risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Marketing reports will take slightly longer to compile</b>: reporting delay is a minor inconvenience compared to the systemic architecture and control risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-049","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is evaluating recovery strategy options for a moderately critical application with an RTO of 24 hours and a limited budget. Which recovery site strategy is MOST appropriate?","options":["A warm site, balancing reasonable recovery speed against cost given the moderate RTO","A fully mirrored hot site with real-time replication regardless of cost","No recovery site at all, relying only on offsite backup tapes with no infrastructure","A cold site with a 30-day equipment procurement lead time"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A warm site, balancing reasonable recovery speed against cost given the moderate RTO</strong> — a warm site, with partially configured infrastructure that can be activated more quickly than a cold site, appropriately matches a 24-hour RTO without the high ongoing cost of a fully mirrored hot site.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A fully mirrored hot site with real-time replication regardless of cost</b>: this exceeds what is needed for a 24-hour RTO and disregards the stated budget constraint.</span> <span class='qd'><b>No recovery site at all, relying only on offsite backup tapes with no infrastructure</b>: this would likely take far longer than 24 hours to restore full operations, failing the RTO.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A cold site with a 30-day equipment procurement lead time</b>: a 30-day lead time is grossly incompatible with a 24-hour recovery requirement.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-050","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization grants temporary elevated access to a contractor to complete a two-week system migration. The contractor's engagement ends, but no process exists to automatically revoke the elevated access. Which control would MOST effectively prevent this risk from recurring?","options":["Manually reminding the contractor's manager by email at an unspecified future date","Time-bound, automatically expiring access provisioned through a formal access request and deprovisioning workflow","Granting all contractors permanent standard access to avoid repeated provisioning","Relying on the contractor to self-report when access should be removed"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Time-bound, automatically expiring access provisioned through a formal access request and deprovisioning workflow</strong> — automating expiration at the time of provisioning removes reliance on manual follow-up and ensures elevated access cannot outlive its legitimate business need.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Manually reminding the contractor's manager by email at an unspecified future date</b>: an informal, undated reminder is unreliable and prone to being missed, as already demonstrated.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting all contractors permanent standard access to avoid repeated provisioning</b>: this increases risk further by making unnecessary access the default rather than addressing the deprovisioning gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Relying on the contractor to self-report when access should be removed</b>: depending on the access holder to police their own privileges is not a reliable or auditable control.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-051","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"easy","q":"Maintaining an accurate, up-to-date IT asset inventory is a foundational control that PRIMARILY supports:","options":["Effective vulnerability management, patching, and risk assessment across known systems","Faster onboarding of new employees","Reduced need for network firewalls","Lower software licensing costs in all cases"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Effective vulnerability management, patching, and risk assessment across known systems</strong> — an accurate asset inventory is the foundation for knowing what needs to be patched, monitored, and assessed; without it, risk activities cannot reliably cover the full environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Faster onboarding of new employees</b>: onboarding speed is unrelated to the purpose of maintaining an asset inventory.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduced need for network firewalls</b>: asset inventories do not reduce the need for network-layer security controls.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Lower software licensing costs in all cases</b>: while inventories can help avoid duplicate licenses, this is a secondary benefit, not the primary risk-related purpose.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-052","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"A software vendor releases a critical patch for a vulnerability actively being exploited in the wild. The organization's standard change process normally requires two weeks of testing before production deployment. As the risk practitioner, what should be recommended?","options":["Follow the standard two-week process without exception regardless of active exploitation","Use an expedited/emergency change process with proportionate testing to deploy the patch faster given active exploitation","Delay patching until the next scheduled quarterly maintenance window","Ignore the patch since testing delays are unavoidable"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Use an expedited/emergency change process with proportionate testing to deploy the patch faster given active exploitation</strong> — when a vulnerability is being actively exploited, the risk of delay outweighs the risk of expedited deployment, justifying use of an emergency change path with risk-appropriate, condensed testing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Follow the standard two-week process without exception regardless of active exploitation</b>: rigidly following the standard timeline ignores the elevated urgency of active exploitation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delay patching until the next scheduled quarterly maintenance window</b>: this leaves the organization exposed to a known, actively exploited vulnerability for an unacceptably long period.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the patch since testing delays are unavoidable</b>: dismissing the patch entirely leaves critical exposure unaddressed and disregards available expedited options.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-053","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"Assigning a data classification level (e.g., public, internal, confidential, restricted) to newly created information is MOST important because it:","options":["Automatically encrypts the data without further action","Eliminates the need for future data classification reviews","Determines the appropriate handling, access, and protection controls to apply throughout the data's lifecycle","Guarantees compliance with all applicable regulations"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Determines the appropriate handling, access, and protection controls to apply throughout the data's lifecycle</strong> — classification at creation establishes the baseline for how the data should be stored, accessed, transmitted, and eventually disposed of, driving proportionate control selection.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Automatically encrypts the data without further action</b>: classification informs which controls should be applied but does not itself perform encryption.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminates the need for future data classification reviews</b>: classification should be periodically reassessed as data or its context changes.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Guarantees compliance with all applicable regulations</b>: classification supports compliance efforts but does not by itself guarantee full regulatory compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-054","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"hard","q":"A large transformation program consists of ten interdependent projects managed under a single portfolio. One project's delayed delivery of a shared authentication service is now blocking three downstream projects from completing security testing. What should the risk practitioner recommend to portfolio governance?","options":["Allow each project team to independently decide how to proceed without coordination","Reassess and reprioritize the portfolio schedule and resources to reflect the critical-path dependency risk","Cancel the three downstream projects to avoid further delay","Ignore the dependency since each project has its own separate budget"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Reassess and reprioritize the portfolio schedule and resources to reflect the critical-path dependency risk</strong> — when a shared dependency creates a critical-path bottleneck affecting multiple projects, portfolio-level governance must reassess priorities and resource allocation to manage the cascading schedule risk holistically.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allow each project team to independently decide how to proceed without coordination</b>: uncoordinated, siloed decisions on a shared dependency risk conflicting actions and further delay.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cancel the three downstream projects to avoid further delay</b>: cancellation is a disproportionate response to a schedule dependency that can likely be managed through reprioritization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the dependency since each project has its own separate budget</b>: separate budgets do not eliminate the technical and schedule dependency risk between projects.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-055","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"An organization's cloud-hosted application relies on a single availability zone with no failover configured. Which risk treatment would MOST directly improve technology resilience for this application?","options":["Configure multi-availability-zone or multi-region redundancy with automated failover","Increase the frequency of user acceptance testing","Add more unit tests to the application's codebase","Reduce the number of application features to simplify the code"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Configure multi-availability-zone or multi-region redundancy with automated failover</strong> — resilience against zone-level outages requires redundancy across multiple availability zones or regions, with automated failover to maintain availability if the primary zone fails.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the frequency of user acceptance testing</b>: UAT validates functional correctness, not infrastructure resilience against outages.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Add more unit tests to the application's codebase</b>: unit testing improves code quality but does not address single-zone infrastructure risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the number of application features to simplify the code</b>: reducing features does not address the underlying lack of infrastructure redundancy.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-056","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating a generative AI tool that employees would use to draft internal documents, some of which may contain proprietary information. The vendor's terms indicate that submitted data may be used to further train the vendor's models. As the risk practitioner, what is the MOST significant risk to flag?","options":["Employees may find the tool's writing style inconsistent with corporate branding","The tool may be slower than existing word processing software","The vendor may discontinue the product in the future","Proprietary or sensitive information could be incorporated into the vendor's model and potentially exposed to other customers"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Proprietary or sensitive information could be incorporated into the vendor's model and potentially exposed to other customers</strong> — if submitted data trains a shared model, proprietary or confidential content risks leaking into outputs generated for other customers, representing a significant confidentiality and competitive risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Employees may find the tool's writing style inconsistent with corporate branding</b>: style consistency is a minor usability concern, not a material risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The tool may be slower than existing word processing software</b>: performance speed is an operational inconvenience, not the primary risk of concern here.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The vendor may discontinue the product in the future</b>: vendor viability is a valid consideration but secondary to the immediate data confidentiality exposure described.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-057","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"An organization is deciding between building a custom control framework from scratch versus adapting a widely recognized framework such as NIST CSF to its context. Which factor MOST supports adapting the recognized framework?","options":["It guarantees the organization will never be audited","It leverages established, tested control structures and common terminology, reducing the effort and risk of gaps versus building from scratch","It requires no customization whatsoever to fit any organization","It eliminates the need for any executive sponsorship"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It leverages established, tested control structures and common terminology, reducing the effort and risk of gaps versus building from scratch</strong> — adapting a recognized framework benefits from industry-vetted structure and shared terminology, lowering the risk of overlooking key control areas compared to building an entirely custom model.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It guarantees the organization will never be audited</b>: no framework choice affects whether the organization will be subject to audit.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It requires no customization whatsoever to fit any organization</b>: recognized frameworks still require tailoring to the specific organization's context and risk profile.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for any executive sponsorship</b>: executive sponsorship remains necessary regardless of which framework is adopted.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-058","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"Requiring a manager's approval before granting a new employee access to a sensitive financial application is an example of which type of control?","options":["Detective control","Corrective control","Preventive access control","Compensating control"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Preventive access control</strong> — requiring approval before access is granted stops inappropriate access from being provisioned in the first place, which is the defining characteristic of a preventive control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Detective control</b>: detective controls identify issues after they occur, such as through log review, not before access is granted.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Corrective control</b>: corrective controls remediate an issue after it has happened, not prevent it upfront.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Compensating control</b>: a compensating control substitutes for a primary control that cannot be implemented, which is not the scenario described.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-059","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"After a significant security incident caused by an employee falling for a targeted phishing email, management asks the risk practitioner to recommend a longer-term improvement beyond the immediate technical remediation. What should be recommended?","options":["Increase firewall throughput capacity","Purchase additional antivirus licenses for all endpoints","Enhance the security awareness program with scenario-based training reflecting the specific attack technique used","Disable all email attachments organization-wide permanently"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Enhance the security awareness program with scenario-based training reflecting the specific attack technique used</strong> — tailoring awareness training to reflect the actual attack technique observed helps employees recognize similar future attempts, directly addressing the human-factor root cause.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase firewall throughput capacity</b>: firewall capacity addresses network performance, not the human susceptibility that enabled the phishing success.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Purchase additional antivirus licenses for all endpoints</b>: antivirus licensing does not address the underlying awareness gap that allowed the phishing email to succeed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disable all email attachments organization-wide permanently</b>: this is an extreme operational disruption disproportionate to the awareness gap identified.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-060","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"A multinational organization transfers employee personal data from the EU to a processing center in a country without an adequacy decision. Legal counsel confirms standard contractual clauses (SCCs) have been executed. As the risk practitioner, what additional step should still be evaluated?","options":["Whether the transfer can be canceled entirely to avoid any further analysis","Whether the SCCs alone are sufficient without any further risk assessment","Whether the data can be reclassified as non-personal to avoid transfer restrictions","Whether supplementary technical and organizational measures are needed given the destination country's surveillance laws and practices"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether supplementary technical and organizational measures are needed given the destination country's surveillance laws and practices</strong> — following relevant guidance on international transfers, SCCs alone may not be sufficient if the destination country's laws could undermine the protections; a transfer impact assessment evaluating supplementary measures (e.g., additional encryption, access restrictions) is a necessary further step.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the transfer can be canceled entirely to avoid any further analysis</b>: canceling the transfer may not be necessary or aligned with legitimate business needs; proper assessment should precede such a drastic step.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the SCCs alone are sufficient without any further risk assessment</b>: this is the opposite of the recommended practice, which requires assessing whether SCCs need to be supplemented.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the data can be reclassified as non-personal to avoid transfer restrictions</b>: reclassifying data to sidestep protection requirements misrepresents its nature and is not a legitimate risk treatment.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-061","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"During an enterprise architecture review, a risk practitioner finds several critical applications still depend on an unsupported operating system version with no vendor security patches available. What is the MOST appropriate immediate recommendation?","options":["Continue operating the applications unchanged since they have not yet been breached","Disconnect the applications from all networks permanently without a transition plan","Wait for the next annual budget cycle before taking any action","Implement compensating controls (network isolation, enhanced monitoring) while accelerating migration to a supported platform"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Implement compensating controls (network isolation, enhanced monitoring) while accelerating migration to a supported platform</strong> — since the unsupported OS cannot receive patches, compensating controls limit exposure in the interim while migration to a supported, maintained platform is prioritized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Continue operating the applications unchanged since they have not yet been breached</b>: absence of a breach so far does not indicate the risk is acceptable; unpatched systems remain a known, growing exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disconnect the applications from all networks permanently without a transition plan</b>: this would likely disrupt critical business operations without a managed transition.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Wait for the next annual budget cycle before taking any action</b>: delaying any interim risk treatment leaves known vulnerabilities unaddressed for an extended period.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-062","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"hard","q":"A post-incident review determines that an unauthorized configuration change caused a major outage, and the change had been approved through the formal change process by an approver who did not have the technical expertise to evaluate its risk. What systemic issue should the risk practitioner highlight?","options":["The change approval workflow lacks a requirement for technically qualified review commensurate with the change's risk","The organization needs a larger change advisory board regardless of expertise","The incident response team responded too slowly","The outage should be reclassified as a natural disaster"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The change approval workflow lacks a requirement for technically qualified review commensurate with the change's risk</strong> — the root systemic gap is that approval authority was not matched to the technical risk of the change, allowing an inadequately vetted change to proceed; the process should require review by someone capable of assessing that risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization needs a larger change advisory board regardless of expertise</b>: simply adding more approvers without ensuring technical competence does not resolve the actual gap.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The incident response team responded too slowly</b>: the scenario centers on a flawed approval process, not the speed of incident response.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The outage should be reclassified as a natural disaster</b>: this is factually incorrect and irrelevant; the outage was caused by a human process failure, not a natural event.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-063","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"A software vendor's SDLC includes a mandatory security gate before code can be merged to the main branch, but developers routinely override the gate using an administrative bypass when facing deadline pressure. What is the MOST effective way to address this risk?","options":["Remove the security gate entirely since it is frequently bypassed anyway","Allow unrestricted bypass access for all developers to reduce delays","Ignore the bypass pattern since deadlines are a normal part of software delivery","Restrict bypass privileges to a limited, accountable group and require documented justification and post-merge review for any bypass used"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Restrict bypass privileges to a limited, accountable group and require documented justification and post-merge review for any bypass used</strong> — tightening who can invoke the bypass and requiring accountability and after-the-fact review restores control effectiveness while allowing legitimate exceptions under scrutiny.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove the security gate entirely since it is frequently bypassed anyway</b>: eliminating the control entirely removes any protection rather than fixing the governance of exceptions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allow unrestricted bypass access for all developers to reduce delays</b>: broadening bypass access would make the control gap worse, not better.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the bypass pattern since deadlines are a normal part of software delivery</b>: normalizing the bypass pattern accepts an unmanaged control weakness without justification.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-064","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner discovers that production customer data, including unmasked personal information, is routinely copied into a non-production test environment with weaker access controls. What is the MOST appropriate treatment?","options":["Implement data masking or synthetic data generation for non-production environments handling sensitive data","Apply the same weak access controls to the production environment for consistency","Discontinue all testing activities until further notice","Reclassify the test environment as production to simplify governance"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Implement data masking or synthetic data generation for non-production environments handling sensitive data</strong> — masking or generating synthetic data for test environments preserves realistic data structures for testing while eliminating the exposure of real sensitive information in a less-controlled environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Apply the same weak access controls to the production environment for consistency</b>: weakening production controls to match test environment weaknesses would increase overall risk rather than reduce it.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Discontinue all testing activities until further notice</b>: halting testing entirely is a disproportionate response when data masking can resolve the exposure while preserving testing capability.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reclassify the test environment as production to simplify governance</b>: relabeling the environment does not address the underlying control gap or reduce actual risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-065","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"easy","q":"Including a risk register as a standing artifact reviewed at every project or sprint milestone PRIMARILY helps ensure that:","options":["The project team no longer needs a project charter","Identified risks remain visible and are actively tracked for treatment throughout delivery","All risks are automatically transferred to insurance","The project's budget is permanently fixed"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Identified risks remain visible and are actively tracked for treatment throughout delivery</strong> — a regularly reviewed risk register keeps known risks in view of the team and stakeholders so that treatment actions and status are actively managed rather than forgotten after initial identification.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The project team no longer needs a project charter</b>: a risk register and a project charter serve entirely different purposes; one does not replace the other.</span> <span class='qd'><b>All risks are automatically transferred to insurance</b>: maintaining a register does not itself transfer risk; risk transfer is a distinct treatment decision.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The project's budget is permanently fixed</b>: a risk register has no bearing on whether the budget is fixed or can be adjusted.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-066","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is reviewing resilience for a critical order-fulfillment system. The business states any outage longer than 2 hours results in significant financial and reputational harm, but no RTO has ever been formally documented for this system. What should be done FIRST?","options":["Immediately purchase additional server hardware without further analysis","Assume the existing infrastructure already meets business needs","Wait for an actual outage to determine the true recovery requirement","Conduct or update the business impact analysis to formally define and document the RTO based on the stated business impact"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Conduct or update the business impact analysis to formally define and document the RTO based on the stated business impact</strong> — before selecting or validating a recovery strategy, the business impact must be formally analyzed and translated into a documented RTO so that resilience investments can be properly justified and measured against it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Immediately purchase additional server hardware without further analysis</b>: acquiring hardware before defining the actual requirement risks misaligned or wasted investment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assume the existing infrastructure already meets business needs</b>: assuming adequacy without formal analysis is precisely the gap that needs to be closed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Wait for an actual outage to determine the true recovery requirement</b>: waiting for a real outage to learn the requirement is reactive and could cause the very harm the business is trying to avoid.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-067","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"An organization plans to migrate a mission-critical application to a serverless cloud architecture to reduce infrastructure management overhead. Which risk is MOST important to evaluate as part of this decision?","options":["Whether the serverless platform uses a visually appealing management console","Whether competitors have already adopted serverless architectures","The color scheme options available for the cloud provider's dashboard","Vendor lock-in and reduced portability, along with new monitoring and security responsibilities specific to the serverless model"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Vendor lock-in and reduced portability, along with new monitoring and security responsibilities specific to the serverless model</strong> — serverless adoption shifts operational responsibility and can deepen dependency on a specific provider's proprietary services, both of which are material risks requiring evaluation before migration.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the serverless platform uses a visually appealing management console</b>: console aesthetics are irrelevant to the risk of the architectural decision.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether competitors have already adopted serverless architectures</b>: competitor behavior does not determine this organization's own specific risk exposure.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The color scheme options available for the cloud provider's dashboard</b>: this is a trivial cosmetic detail with no risk relevance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-068","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"med","q":"An internal audit finds that the organization has documented control objectives aligned to a recognized framework, but no evidence exists that the controls are operating effectively in practice. What is the MOST significant risk this represents?","options":["The framework selected was the wrong one for the organization","The audit team lacks sufficient headcount","The controls need to be renamed to match updated framework terminology","A false sense of assurance, since documented design does not confirm the controls are functioning as intended"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>A false sense of assurance, since documented design does not confirm the controls are functioning as intended</strong> — having controls mapped and documented on paper without operating effectiveness evidence creates a dangerous gap between perceived and actual risk coverage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The framework selected was the wrong one for the organization</b>: the scenario does not indicate the framework itself is unsuitable, only that operating evidence is missing.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The audit team lacks sufficient headcount</b>: staffing levels are not indicated as the cause of the finding described.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The controls need to be renamed to match updated framework terminology</b>: naming conventions are a cosmetic issue, not the substantive risk identified.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-069","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is implementing a zero trust architecture. Which principle BEST reflects the core risk-reduction philosophy of zero trust as compared to a traditional perimeter-based model?","options":["Grant broad implicit trust to any device once it connects to the internal network","Rely solely on a strong perimeter firewall as the primary control","Disable all authentication for internal systems to improve usability","Continuously verify every access request based on identity, device posture, and context, rather than trusting anything inside the network perimeter by default"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Continuously verify every access request based on identity, device posture, and context, rather than trusting anything inside the network perimeter by default</strong> — zero trust replaces implicit trust based on network location with continuous, contextual verification of every access attempt, reducing the risk posed by compromised internal accounts or devices.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Grant broad implicit trust to any device once it connects to the internal network</b>: this describes the legacy perimeter-trust model that zero trust is specifically designed to replace.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Rely solely on a strong perimeter firewall as the primary control</b>: perimeter-only reliance is the traditional model zero trust moves away from, since it does not address threats already inside the network.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Disable all authentication for internal systems to improve usability</b>: this is the opposite of zero trust, which requires continuous verification, not the removal of authentication.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-070","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"easy","q":"A new hire completes mandatory security awareness training on their first day but receives no further reinforcement for the remainder of the year. From a risk perspective, this approach is MOST likely to result in:","options":["Permanent retention of all training content with no further need for review","A reduced likelihood of ever falling for a phishing attempt","Full compliance with all data protection regulations automatically","Declining retention of secure behaviors over time without periodic reinforcement"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Declining retention of secure behaviors over time without periodic reinforcement</strong> — a single onboarding session without ongoing reinforcement is well known to result in fading awareness and behavior drift over time, increasing susceptibility to social engineering as the months pass.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Permanent retention of all training content with no further need for review</b>: this contradicts well-established evidence that awareness and behavior decay without reinforcement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A reduced likelihood of ever falling for a phishing attempt</b>: one-time training without reinforcement does not sustain reduced susceptibility over an entire year.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Full compliance with all data protection regulations automatically</b>: completing onboarding training does not by itself ensure ongoing regulatory compliance.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-071","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is asked to recommend a control to reduce the risk of sensitive data being unintentionally emailed to external recipients. Which control BEST addresses this specific risk?","options":["A stronger corporate firewall at the network perimeter","Mandatory two-factor authentication for internal file servers","A data loss prevention (DLP) solution configured to detect and block outbound sensitive data patterns","Encrypting data only while it is stored on internal servers"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A data loss prevention (DLP) solution configured to detect and block outbound sensitive data patterns</strong> — DLP tools are purpose-built to inspect outbound communications, including email, and block or flag transmissions containing sensitive data patterns before they leave the organization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A stronger corporate firewall at the network perimeter</b>: a firewall primarily filters network traffic based on rules and does not inspect email content for sensitive data patterns.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Mandatory two-factor authentication for internal file servers</b>: MFA strengthens authentication but does not prevent authorized users from mistakenly emailing sensitive data externally.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Encrypting data only while it is stored on internal servers</b>: encryption at rest does not prevent an authorized user from sending unencrypted sensitive data via email.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-072","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is asked to assess the risk of an organization's enterprise architecture becoming misaligned with business strategy after a major merger. Which indicator would BEST reveal early signs of this misalignment?","options":["An increase in the number of scheduled architecture review meetings","A growing number of duplicate or conflicting systems performing the same business function across the merged entities","A decrease in the total number of applications in the portfolio","An increase in employee satisfaction survey scores"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A growing number of duplicate or conflicting systems performing the same business function across the merged entities</strong> — post-merger duplication of overlapping systems is a direct, measurable early sign that the combined enterprise architecture has not been rationalized against the unified business strategy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>An increase in the number of scheduled architecture review meetings</b>: meeting frequency is an activity metric, not evidence of actual alignment or misalignment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A decrease in the total number of applications in the portfolio</b>: a decreasing count could actually indicate successful rationalization, the opposite of the misalignment being assessed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>An increase in employee satisfaction survey scores</b>: satisfaction scores are unrelated to whether the technical architecture aligns with business strategy.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-073","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"An organization's asset disposal process for retired laptops relies on employees returning devices to IT, but there is no formal verification that data has been securely wiped before the devices are resold. What is the MOST significant risk this creates?","options":["The organization will receive a lower resale value for the laptops","IT staff will need to spend more time processing returns","The laptops may have a shorter remaining useful life","Residual sensitive data on disposed devices could be exposed to unauthorized parties after resale"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Residual sensitive data on disposed devices could be exposed to unauthorized parties after resale</strong> — without verified secure wiping, data remaining on the storage media could be recovered by whoever acquires the device after resale, creating a real confidentiality risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will receive a lower resale value for the laptops</b>: resale value is a financial consideration, not the primary security risk of concern.</span> <span class='qd'><b>IT staff will need to spend more time processing returns</b>: processing time is an operational efficiency matter, not the core data exposure risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The laptops may have a shorter remaining useful life</b>: device lifespan is unrelated to the risk of residual data exposure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-074","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes the relationship between recovery time objective (RTO) and recovery point objective (RPO)?","options":["RTO addresses acceptable downtime, while RPO addresses acceptable data loss measured in time","RTO and RPO both measure the same thing using different units","RPO addresses acceptable downtime, while RTO addresses acceptable data loss","Neither metric is relevant to disaster recovery planning"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>RTO addresses acceptable downtime, while RPO addresses acceptable data loss measured in time</strong> — RTO defines how long a system can be unavailable before recovery, while RPO defines how much data (measured in time since the last capture) can be acceptably lost; the two address distinct dimensions of resilience.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>RTO and RPO both measure the same thing using different units</b>: the two metrics measure fundamentally different concepts (downtime versus data loss), not the same thing.</span> <span class='qd'><b>RPO addresses acceptable downtime, while RTO addresses acceptable data loss</b>: this reverses the correct definitions of the two metrics.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither metric is relevant to disaster recovery planning</b>: both RTO and RPO are foundational, directly relevant metrics in disaster recovery and business continuity planning.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-075","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"An organization is considering allowing employees to use personal mobile devices to access corporate email under a bring-your-own-device (BYOD) program. Which control would MOST effectively reduce the associated data risk while respecting the personal nature of the device?","options":["Granting full administrative access to IT over the entire personal device","A mobile device management (MDM) solution that enforces a containerized, encrypted corporate workspace separate from personal data","Prohibiting any encryption on the device to simplify support","Allowing corporate data to be freely copied into any personal app without restriction"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A mobile device management (MDM) solution that enforces a containerized, encrypted corporate workspace separate from personal data</strong> — containerization isolates and encrypts corporate data within its own managed workspace, allowing enforcement of corporate security policy without the organization needing full control over the employee's personal device or data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting full administrative access to IT over the entire personal device</b>: this is overly invasive of personal privacy and disproportionate to the actual risk being managed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Prohibiting any encryption on the device to simplify support</b>: removing encryption would increase, not decrease, the risk of data exposure if the device is lost or compromised.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing corporate data to be freely copied into any personal app without restriction</b>: this would significantly increase the risk of corporate data leakage into uncontrolled personal applications.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-076","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"An organization selects a control framework primarily because it is the most widely cited in industry publications, without assessing fit to its own risk profile. This approach BEST illustrates the risk of:","options":["Adopting controls that may not address the organization's actual, specific risk exposures","Achieving guaranteed regulatory compliance in every jurisdiction","Eliminating the need for any future risk assessments","Reducing the overall cost of the security program to zero"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Adopting controls that may not address the organization's actual, specific risk exposures</strong> — choosing a framework based on popularity rather than fit risks implementing controls that do not match the organization's actual threat landscape, business model, or regulatory context.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Achieving guaranteed regulatory compliance in every jurisdiction</b>: no framework choice, however popular, guarantees compliance across all jurisdictions.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminating the need for any future risk assessments</b>: ongoing risk assessment remains necessary regardless of which framework is selected.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reducing the overall cost of the security program to zero</b>: framework selection does not eliminate program costs; this option is an unrealistic claim.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-077","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"An organization is designing access controls for a new cloud-based document repository containing contracts of varying sensitivity. Which approach BEST supports appropriate risk-based access management?","options":["Attribute-based or role-based access aligned to document classification and business need-to-know","Granting all employees read access to every document for transparency","Assigning access based solely on employee tenure with the company","Allowing any employee to reclassify documents at their own discretion"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Attribute-based or role-based access aligned to document classification and business need-to-know</strong> — tying access to classification and legitimate need-to-know ensures that sensitivity level and job function jointly determine appropriate access, minimizing unnecessary exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting all employees read access to every document for transparency</b>: blanket access disregards sensitivity levels and dramatically increases exposure of confidential contracts.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Assigning access based solely on employee tenure with the company</b>: tenure has no logical connection to whether an employee has a legitimate business need to view specific documents.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Allowing any employee to reclassify documents at their own discretion</b>: unrestricted reclassification undermines the integrity of the classification scheme and could be used to bypass controls.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-078","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner notices that security awareness training content has not been updated to reflect a recent rise in deepfake-based voice phishing (vishing) attacks targeting the organization's finance team. What should be recommended?","options":["Continue using the existing training content since it previously passed review","Remove vishing from the training curriculum since it is a newer, less understood threat","Update training content and simulations to address the specific emerging deepfake vishing threat targeting finance staff","Transfer all responsibility for this risk to the telecom provider"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Update training content and simulations to address the specific emerging deepfake vishing threat targeting finance staff</strong> — training must evolve to reflect current, targeted threats; updating content and running realistic simulations for the finance team directly addresses this emerging attack vector.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Continue using the existing training content since it previously passed review</b>: outdated content that ignores an emerging, targeted threat leaves staff unprepared for current attack methods.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Remove vishing from the training curriculum since it is a newer, less understood threat</b>: removing coverage of an active, relevant threat is counterproductive and increases risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Transfer all responsibility for this risk to the telecom provider</b>: a telecom provider cannot mitigate the human-factor risk of employees being deceived by fraudulent calls.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-079","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is designing a data protection strategy for a new product that collects biometric data from users. Which control consideration is MOST critical given the heightened sensitivity of biometric information?","options":["Standard password-based access controls identical to those used for general employee email","Storing biometric data in the same repository as general marketing data for convenience","Enhanced encryption, strict access limitation, and explicit legal basis/consent requirements specific to biometric data categories","Applying the organization's lowest data classification tier to reduce handling costs"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Enhanced encryption, strict access limitation, and explicit legal basis/consent requirements specific to biometric data categories</strong> — biometric data is typically treated as a special or sensitive data category under privacy laws, requiring heightened technical protection and a clear legal basis or explicit consent for its collection and use.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Standard password-based access controls identical to those used for general employee email</b>: applying only baseline controls understates the heightened protection biometric data warrants.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Storing biometric data in the same repository as general marketing data for convenience</b>: comingling highly sensitive biometric data with lower-sensitivity marketing data increases exposure and complicates control enforcement.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Applying the organization's lowest data classification tier to reduce handling costs</b>: under-classifying biometric data would result in insufficient protection given its actual sensitivity.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-080","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"med","q":"A project team is deciding whether to conduct security testing only at the end of the SDLC (a single pre-release gate) or to integrate testing continuously throughout development (a 'shift-left' approach). From a risk perspective, which approach BEST reduces overall risk and cost?","options":["A single pre-release gate, since it consolidates all testing effort into one predictable checkpoint","Neither approach matters, since testing timing has no bearing on risk or cost","Testing only in production, since real-world conditions provide the most accurate results","Shift-left, continuous testing throughout development, since defects are cheaper and less risky to fix earlier"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Shift-left, continuous testing throughout development, since defects are cheaper and less risky to fix earlier</strong> — integrating security testing continuously throughout development identifies and remediates issues while they are still inexpensive and low-risk to fix, rather than accumulating them until a single late-stage gate.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A single pre-release gate, since it consolidates all testing effort into one predictable checkpoint</b>: concentrating all testing at the end increases the cost and risk of late-discovered defects and can create release-schedule pressure to bypass remediation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither approach matters, since testing timing has no bearing on risk or cost</b>: this contradicts well-established evidence that earlier defect discovery is significantly less costly and risky to remediate.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Testing only in production, since real-world conditions provide the most accurate results</b>: testing exclusively in production exposes real users and data to unmitigated risk from undiscovered defects.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-081","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following is the PRIMARY risk of failing to classify data upon creation?","options":["The data will automatically be deleted after 30 days","The organization will be unable to back up the data","Users will be unable to open the file at all","Inconsistent or inadequate protection may be applied because handling requirements are undefined"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Inconsistent or inadequate protection may be applied because handling requirements are undefined</strong> — without classification, there is no clear signal for how the data should be protected, leading to either under-protection of sensitive data or unnecessary overhead on non-sensitive data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The data will automatically be deleted after 30 days</b>: classification status does not trigger automatic deletion timelines by itself.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization will be unable to back up the data</b>: lack of classification does not prevent standard backup processes from running.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Users will be unable to open the file at all</b>: classification status does not affect a file's basic accessibility or usability.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-082","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"A technology project portfolio prioritization model currently ranks projects solely by expected financial return, without considering associated risk exposure. What is the MOST significant limitation of this approach from a risk practitioner's perspective?","options":["Financial return is an irrelevant factor in any prioritization model","The model will automatically underfund all low-risk projects","Project managers will need less training under this model","High-return projects with unacceptably high risk exposure may be prioritized over lower-return, lower-risk initiatives without adequate risk-adjusted comparison"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>High-return projects with unacceptably high risk exposure may be prioritized over lower-return, lower-risk initiatives without adequate risk-adjusted comparison</strong> — ranking by return alone ignores the risk dimension, potentially directing resources to initiatives whose risk exposure has not been weighed against the expected benefit.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Financial return is an irrelevant factor in any prioritization model</b>: financial return is a legitimate and important factor; the issue is that it is being used in isolation without risk context.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The model will automatically underfund all low-risk projects</b>: the scenario does not establish that low-risk projects are systematically underfunded, only that risk is not factored in at all.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Project managers will need less training under this model</b>: training needs are unrelated to the prioritization criteria used in the model.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-083","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is reviewing resilience investment options for a critical application. Option A costs $500,000 annually and reduces expected annual downtime-related loss from $2,000,000 to $300,000. Option B costs $150,000 annually and reduces the same expected loss to $900,000. From a risk-based cost-benefit perspective, which option provides the BETTER net risk reduction value?","options":["Option B, since it has the lowest absolute cost regardless of net benefit","Both options are equivalent since they address the same original risk","Neither option should be pursued since both still leave residual risk","Option A, since its net benefit ($2,000,000 - $300,000 - $500,000 = $1,200,000) exceeds Option B's net benefit ($2,000,000 - $900,000 - $150,000 = $950,000)"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Option A, since its net benefit ($2,000,000 - $300,000 - $500,000 = $1,200,000) exceeds Option B's net benefit ($2,000,000 - $900,000 - $150,000 = $950,000)</strong> — comparing net risk reduction (avoided loss minus cost) shows Option A delivers greater overall value despite its higher price tag, because it drives down expected loss more substantially.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Option B, since it has the lowest absolute cost regardless of net benefit</b>: focusing on cost alone ignores the greater overall value Option A provides once loss reduction is factored in.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Both options are equivalent since they address the same original risk</b>: the two options produce materially different net benefits and are not equivalent in value.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Neither option should be pursued since both still leave residual risk</b>: some residual risk is expected and acceptable; the comparison should still identify the better of the two available options.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-084","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"med","q":"An organization is adopting a hybrid cloud strategy, keeping sensitive workloads on-premises while migrating less sensitive workloads to a public cloud provider. Which risk consideration is MOST important when designing connectivity between the two environments?","options":["Selecting the cloud provider with the most colorful marketing materials","Securing and monitoring the interconnection point to prevent it from becoming an unmonitored bridge between trust zones","Ensuring both environments use identical physical hardware vendors","Minimizing the number of cloud administrators regardless of their access needs"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Securing and monitoring the interconnection point to prevent it from becoming an unmonitored bridge between trust zones</strong> — the connection between on-premises and cloud environments is a critical control point; without proper security and monitoring, it can become a pathway for lateral movement between environments of differing trust levels.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Selecting the cloud provider with the most colorful marketing materials</b>: marketing presentation has no bearing on the technical risk of the interconnection.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ensuring both environments use identical physical hardware vendors</b>: hardware vendor matching is not a meaningful risk factor for hybrid cloud connectivity security.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Minimizing the number of cloud administrators regardless of their access needs</b>: administrator count without regard to actual access needs does not directly address the interconnection risk described.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-085","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is advising a subsidiary that must comply with both a strict national cybersecurity law and the parent company's globally adopted security framework, which conflict on certain encryption key-length requirements. What is the MOST appropriate approach?","options":["Ignore the national law since the parent company's framework takes precedence globally","Apply the more stringent of the two conflicting requirements where legally permissible, and formally document the resolution and any exceptions","Ignore the parent company's framework since local law always governs entirely","Apply neither requirement until the conflict is resolved by external legal counsel"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Apply the more stringent of the two conflicting requirements where legally permissible, and formally document the resolution and any exceptions</strong> — when requirements conflict, applying the stricter standard (where legally allowed) typically satisfies both, and formally documenting the resolution ensures accountability and auditability of the decision.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the national law since the parent company's framework takes precedence globally</b>: internal corporate policy cannot override binding local legal requirements.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Ignore the parent company's framework since local law always governs entirely</b>: dismissing the corporate framework entirely may leave gaps the local law does not address and disregards enterprise governance.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Apply neither requirement until the conflict is resolved by external legal counsel</b>: leaving both requirements unmet in the interim creates unnecessary compliance exposure while the conflict is being resolved.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-086","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"easy","q":"An organization implements a control requiring two different individuals to jointly authorize any wire transfer above a defined monetary threshold. This is an example of:","options":["Dual control, a form of segregation of duties","A detective control performed after the transaction","A physical security control","A data classification control"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Dual control, a form of segregation of duties</strong> — requiring two individuals to jointly authorize a high-value transaction is a classic dual-control implementation of segregation of duties, preventing any single person from completing the sensitive action alone.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>A detective control performed after the transaction</b>: dual authorization happens before the transaction is completed, making it preventive, not detective.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A physical security control</b>: this control governs authorization of a financial transaction, not physical access to premises or assets.</span> <span class='qd'><b>A data classification control</b>: classification concerns labeling data sensitivity, unrelated to transaction authorization requirements.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-087","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is designing a security awareness program for a global organization with employees across multiple regions and job functions. Which design principle would MOST improve the program's effectiveness?","options":["Using the exact same generic slide deck for every employee regardless of role or region","Delivering training only once, at the time of company founding","Tailoring content and delivery to role-specific risks and regional/cultural context, rather than a single generic module for all staff","Limiting training exclusively to the IT department"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Tailoring content and delivery to role-specific risks and regional/cultural context, rather than a single generic module for all staff</strong> — role-based and regionally relevant training addresses the specific risks each group actually faces (e.g., finance staff and wire fraud, regional regulatory nuances), making the content more relevant and effective than one-size-fits-all delivery.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using the exact same generic slide deck for every employee regardless of role or region</b>: generic, undifferentiated content fails to address the specific risks different roles and regions actually face.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delivering training only once, at the time of company founding</b>: this is impractical and disregards the constant need for onboarding new staff and refreshing existing staff on evolving threats.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Limiting training exclusively to the IT department</b>: excluding non-IT staff ignores the fact that all employees are potential targets of social engineering and human-factor risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-088","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"An organization plans to donate decommissioned hard drives containing former customer records to a local charity after formatting them using the operating system's standard quick-format utility. What is the MOST significant risk with this approach?","options":["Standard quick-format does not securely erase underlying data, which may remain recoverable using data recovery tools","Charities are not permitted to receive any donated equipment under any circumstances","Quick-format takes longer than a full forensic wipe","The hard drives will be physically damaged by the format process"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Standard quick-format does not securely erase underlying data, which may remain recoverable using data recovery tools</strong> — a quick format typically only clears the file allocation table rather than overwriting the actual data, leaving former customer records potentially recoverable by anyone who later accesses the drives.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Charities are not permitted to receive any donated equipment under any circumstances</b>: there is no general prohibition on donating properly sanitized equipment to charities.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Quick-format takes longer than a full forensic wipe</b>: this is factually backwards; a quick format is typically much faster than a secure wipe, not slower.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The hard drives will be physically damaged by the format process</b>: a standard format does not cause physical damage to the drive hardware.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-089","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner is reviewing a proposed technology investment that is not represented anywhere on the current enterprise architecture roadmap. What is the MOST appropriate initial step?","options":["Engage enterprise architecture stakeholders to assess fit, risk, and integration impact before the investment proceeds","Approve the investment immediately since it was independently requested by a business unit","Reject the investment automatically because it is not on the roadmap","Delay indefinitely without further evaluation or stakeholder engagement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Engage enterprise architecture stakeholders to assess fit, risk, and integration impact before the investment proceeds</strong> — an investment outside the current roadmap should be evaluated collaboratively with architecture stakeholders to understand risk, integration implications, and whether the roadmap itself needs to be updated.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Approve the investment immediately since it was independently requested by a business unit</b>: approving without architectural assessment risks introducing unmanaged technical and integration risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reject the investment automatically because it is not on the roadmap</b>: automatic rejection is overly rigid and may block a legitimate, valuable business need without proper evaluation.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delay indefinitely without further evaluation or stakeholder engagement</b>: indefinite delay without engaging stakeholders does not resolve the underlying question of fit and risk.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-090","domain":4,"obj":"4A2","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner reviewing IT operations finds that patch management metrics are reported as 'percentage of patches applied' without regard to the criticality of the underlying vulnerabilities. What is the MOST significant limitation of this metric?","options":["It may create a false sense of security if low-risk patches are prioritized over critical, high-risk vulnerabilities","It requires too much manual effort to calculate each month","It cannot be automated using existing patch management tools","It does not account for the number of help desk tickets generated"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>It may create a false sense of security if low-risk patches are prioritized over critical, high-risk vulnerabilities</strong> — a raw percentage metric treats all patches equally, so an organization could report a high completion rate while critical vulnerabilities remain unpatched, misrepresenting actual risk exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>It requires too much manual effort to calculate each month</b>: calculation effort is an operational detail, not the core analytical flaw in the metric.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It cannot be automated using existing patch management tools</b>: most patch management tools can generate this percentage automatically; automation is not the issue.</span> <span class='qd'><b>It does not account for the number of help desk tickets generated</b>: ticket volume is unrelated to whether the metric reflects actual risk-based patching priority.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-091","domain":4,"obj":"4A3","diff":"easy","q":"Requiring developers to complete secure coding training as part of the SDLC is PRIMARILY intended to:","options":["Increase the total number of lines of code produced","Reduce the introduction of common coding vulnerabilities into applications during development","Eliminate the need for any post-deployment security testing","Reduce the time required for user acceptance testing"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Reduce the introduction of common coding vulnerabilities into applications during development</strong> — secure coding training equips developers to recognize and avoid common vulnerability patterns (such as injection flaws) before they are written into the codebase, addressing risk at its source.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Increase the total number of lines of code produced</b>: code volume is not a meaningful or intended outcome of secure coding training.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Eliminate the need for any post-deployment security testing</b>: secure coding training reduces but does not eliminate the need for ongoing testing and validation after deployment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Reduce the time required for user acceptance testing</b>: UAT timing is unrelated to the purpose of secure coding training.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-092","domain":4,"obj":"4A4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization operates in a jurisdiction requiring that certain categories of personal data remain physically stored within national borders (data residency). A proposed cloud migration would place backups in a data center located in another country. What should the risk practitioner recommend?","options":["Proceed with the migration as planned since backup location is not legally relevant","Store only production data locally while ignoring backup location entirely","Select a cloud region or provider configuration that keeps in-scope data and backups within the required jurisdiction, or apply compensating legal/technical safeguards","Cancel all cloud migration plans permanently regardless of alternative configurations"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Select a cloud region or provider configuration that keeps in-scope data and backups within the required jurisdiction, or apply compensating legal/technical safeguards</strong> — data residency requirements typically apply to backups as well as production copies, so the migration plan must be adjusted to keep in-scope data within the required jurisdiction or use approved safeguards to remain compliant.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Proceed with the migration as planned since backup location is not legally relevant</b>: backup copies of in-scope data are typically subject to the same residency requirements as production data.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Store only production data locally while ignoring backup location entirely</b>: ignoring backup residency leaves a genuine compliance gap unaddressed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Cancel all cloud migration plans permanently regardless of alternative configurations</b>: cancellation is a disproportionate response when compliant regional configurations or safeguards are typically available.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-093","domain":4,"obj":"4A5","diff":"med","q":"A risk practitioner observes that a project's risk register lists several risks as 'closed' simply because the project moved into its next phase, without any documented treatment or verification. What is the MOST appropriate action?","options":["Accept the closures since phase transitions are a reasonable basis for closing risks","Delete the risk register entirely since it is unreliable","Require that each risk be formally verified as treated, transferred, avoided, or accepted before being marked closed","Escalate every risk to the highest severity rating regardless of actual status"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Require that each risk be formally verified as treated, transferred, avoided, or accepted before being marked closed</strong> — closing a risk should reflect a documented, verified disposition (treated, transferred, avoided, or accepted), not simply the passage of a project milestone, to ensure risks are genuinely managed rather than administratively dismissed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Accept the closures since phase transitions are a reasonable basis for closing risks</b>: a phase transition alone provides no evidence that the underlying risk has actually been addressed.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Delete the risk register entirely since it is unreliable</b>: the register itself remains valuable; the issue is the closure practice, which can be corrected rather than discarding the tool.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Escalate every risk to the highest severity rating regardless of actual status</b>: arbitrarily inflating severity does not address the actual problem of unverified closures and would distort prioritization.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-094","domain":4,"obj":"4A6","diff":"med","q":"An organization's crisis management plan designates a single individual with the sole authority to declare a disaster and activate the recovery site. This individual is unreachable during an actual outage. What is the MOST important lesson for improving technology resilience planning?","options":["The recovery site itself was configured incorrectly","The outage should have been prevented through better firewall rules","The organization should eliminate the disaster declaration process entirely","Recovery and crisis plans should include designated backup decision-makers to avoid a single point of failure in the activation process"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Recovery and crisis plans should include designated backup decision-makers to avoid a single point of failure in the activation process</strong> — reliance on one individual for a critical decision creates a single point of failure in the activation process itself; the plan should name alternates so activation is not delayed if the primary decision-maker is unavailable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The recovery site itself was configured incorrectly</b>: nothing in the scenario indicates the recovery site's technical configuration was the problem; the issue is decision-making authority.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The outage should have been prevented through better firewall rules</b>: the scenario does not attribute the outage's cause to firewall configuration, and this does not address the activation delay.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization should eliminate the disaster declaration process entirely</b>: removing the declaration process would eliminate a necessary governance checkpoint rather than fixing the single point of failure.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-095","domain":4,"obj":"4A7","diff":"hard","q":"An organization is evaluating whether to use a third-party API to enrich customer records with external data in real time. The API provider's uptime SLA is lower than the organization's own customer-facing application SLA. What is the MOST important risk to address before integration?","options":["Whether the API documentation uses consistent formatting","Whether the API provider offers a free trial period","Whether the API supports the organization's preferred programming language exclusively","Whether a dependency failure in the third-party API could degrade or break the organization's own application beyond its committed SLA"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Whether a dependency failure in the third-party API could degrade or break the organization's own application beyond its committed SLA</strong> — integrating a dependency with a weaker SLA than the consuming application risks a cascading availability failure, so the design must include fallback handling (timeouts, graceful degradation) to prevent the third party's outage from breaching the organization's own commitments.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the API documentation uses consistent formatting</b>: documentation style is a developer convenience, not a material availability risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the API provider offers a free trial period</b>: trial availability is a commercial/procurement detail unrelated to the resilience risk of the dependency.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the API supports the organization's preferred programming language exclusively</b>: language compatibility is a technical integration convenience, not the primary availability risk to evaluate.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-096","domain":4,"obj":"4B1","diff":"easy","q":"Which of the following BEST describes why organizations map their internal control set to more than one framework or standard (e.g., both ISO/IEC 27001 and a regional data protection law) rather than relying on just one?","options":["Using multiple frameworks always doubles the total cost of the compliance program","Different frameworks and legal requirements may address distinct but overlapping risk and compliance needs that a single source may not fully cover","Frameworks conflict with one another and cannot be reasonably reconciled","Multiple frameworks are only necessary for publicly traded companies"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Different frameworks and legal requirements may address distinct but overlapping risk and compliance needs that a single source may not fully cover</strong> — a security management standard and a specific data protection law often address different but complementary aspects of risk, so mapping to multiple sources provides more complete coverage than relying on a single standard alone.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Using multiple frameworks always doubles the total cost of the compliance program</b>: mapping to multiple frameworks often reveals overlapping controls that can be satisfied once, avoiding simple cost duplication.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Frameworks conflict with one another and cannot be reasonably reconciled</b>: most recognized frameworks and legal requirements can be reconciled and cross-mapped, rather than being fundamentally incompatible.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Multiple frameworks are only necessary for publicly traded companies</b>: the need to address multiple compliance and risk sources is not limited to publicly traded organizations.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-097","domain":4,"obj":"4B2","diff":"med","q":"A periodic user access review finds several employees retain access to an application from a role they held over a year ago, despite having since transferred to unrelated departments. What control failure does this MOST directly indicate?","options":["The application requires a stronger password policy","Access recertification and deprovisioning upon role change are not being consistently enforced","The organization needs additional firewall rules","The help desk is receiving too many password reset requests"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Access recertification and deprovisioning upon role change are not being consistently enforced</strong> — retained access from a prior, unrelated role well after transfer indicates that the process for reviewing and removing access tied to job function changes is not operating effectively.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>The application requires a stronger password policy</b>: password strength is unrelated to the issue of stale entitlements from a prior role.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The organization needs additional firewall rules</b>: firewall configuration does not address user-level access recertification failures.</span> <span class='qd'><b>The help desk is receiving too many password reset requests</b>: reset volume is unrelated to the access recertification gap identified.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-098","domain":4,"obj":"4B3","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is evaluating the effectiveness of a security awareness program using only the metric 'percentage of employees who completed annual training.' Which additional metric would MOST improve the practitioner's ability to assess actual risk reduction?","options":["Total number of training slides delivered per employee","Number of different languages the training is offered in","Trend in phishing simulation click-through and reporting rates over time","Average time employees spend logged into the training portal"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Trend in phishing simulation click-through and reporting rates over time</strong> — behavioral metrics such as simulated phishing click and reporting rates measure actual changes in employee behavior and susceptibility, providing far more meaningful insight into real risk reduction than mere completion rates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Total number of training slides delivered per employee</b>: slide count is a volume metric with no bearing on whether behavior actually improved.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Number of different languages the training is offered in</b>: language availability supports accessibility but does not measure behavioral risk reduction.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Average time employees spend logged into the training portal</b>: time spent logged in does not indicate whether the training content was retained or behavior changed.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-099","domain":4,"obj":"4B4","diff":"med","q":"An organization wants to allow a business intelligence team to analyze historical sales trends without exposing individual customer identities. Which technique BEST supports this business need while minimizing privacy risk?","options":["Providing the team with full, unmasked access to the raw customer database","Aggregating and anonymizing the data so individual records cannot be re-identified before analysis","Sharing individual customer records but removing only the customer's name field","Granting temporary administrative access to the production database for the duration of the analysis"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Aggregating and anonymizing the data so individual records cannot be re-identified before analysis</strong> — aggregating data to a level where individual customers cannot be re-identified satisfies the analytical need for trend analysis while substantially reducing the privacy risk of exposing personal information.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Providing the team with full, unmasked access to the raw customer database</b>: this exposes far more personal data than necessary for trend analysis, violating data minimization.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Sharing individual customer records but removing only the customer's name field</b>: removing only the name often leaves enough other attributes (e.g., address, purchase history) to allow re-identification.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Granting temporary administrative access to the production database for the duration of the analysis</b>: administrative access grants far broader privileges than needed and increases risk unnecessarily.</span>"},
{"id":"D4-100","domain":4,"obj":"4A1","diff":"hard","q":"A risk practitioner is asked to assess whether a proposed enterprise architecture change (consolidating three regional data centers into one central facility) increases or decreases overall technology risk. Which factor would MOST influence this determination?","options":["Whether the central facility has a more modern reception area","Whether the consolidation introduces a single point of failure that outweighs the benefits of standardization and reduced complexity","Whether the change reduces the number of vendor invoices processed monthly","Whether employees prefer the new facility's location"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Whether the consolidation introduces a single point of failure that outweighs the benefits of standardization and reduced complexity</strong> — while consolidation can reduce architectural complexity and improve consistency, it may concentrate risk into a single facility; the practitioner must weigh this potential single point of failure against the standardization benefits to determine the net risk impact.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the central facility has a more modern reception area</b>: facility aesthetics have no bearing on technology risk assessment.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether the change reduces the number of vendor invoices processed monthly</b>: invoice volume is an administrative efficiency matter, not a determinant of technology risk.</span> <span class='qd'><b>Whether employees prefer the new facility's location</b>: employee location preference is a workplace satisfaction issue, unrelated to the architectural risk assessment.</span>"}
]);
